                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d317">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.114/1032: Circular telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                            <gloss type="to">Diplomatic and Consular Officers</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-10-14">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 14, 1922</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>At request of Secretary of Treasury, send following notice by mail or otherwise
                    to all persons and companies your district owning or operating vessels touching
                    at ports of the United States or any of its possessions, and to masters of such
                    vessels, and give wide publicity to it both in English and in the language of
                    your district.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“The provisions of the National Prohibition Act are applicable to United
                        States vessels leaving foreign ports after October 21st, and to foreign
                        vessels leaving foreign ports after that date on coming within the
                        territorial waters of the United States. All sales of beverage liquors on
                        United States vessels anywhere, and on foreign vessels within the
                        territorial waters of the United States, are unlawful after October 7th.
                        This notice does not apply to foreign vessels passing through the Panama
                        Canal and not touching any other port under the jurisdiction of the United
                        States.</p>
                    <p rend="right">A. W. Mellon<lb/>Secretary of the Treasury.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
